    {
      "question": "The shadow of a tower standing on a level ground is found to be $40$ m longer when the Sun's altitude is $30^\\circ$ than when it is $60^\\circ$. The height of the tower is not required, but if we consider a simpler case where the shadow is $h\\sqrt{3}$ when angle is $30^\\circ$, what is the height $h$ if the shadow is $30$ m?",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "$\\tan(30^\\circ) = \\frac{h}{30}$",
          "$\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{h}{30}$",
          "$h = \\frac{30}{\\sqrt{3}} = 10\\sqrt{3}$"
        ],
        "derivation": "h = 30 \\times \\tan(30^\\circ) = 30 \\times \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} = 10\\sqrt{3}"
